00:11:35.433 --> 00:11:38.411
and "I want to destroy the bastard."

263
00:11:38.478 --> 00:11:41.014
With five exclamation points.

264
00:11:41.114 --> 00:11:44.317
Well. Bella could be a
bit dramatic at times.

265
00:11:44.417 --> 00:11:48.413
but she was a good woman and a
legend in the fashion industry.

266
00:11:48.479 --> 00:11:50.423
Who are you protecting here. Mr. Matz?

267
00:11:50.490 --> 00:11:51.783
And why?

268
00:11:51.849 --> 00:11:53.426
It's nothing like that.

269
00:11:53.493 --> 00:11:56.020
It's just that I adored Bella.

270
00:11:56.087 --> 00:11:58.398
and I don't want to talk out of turn

271
00:11:58.464 --> 00:12:01.200
and tarnish her reputation.

272
00:12:03.161 --> 00:12:05.705
We appreciate that. Mr. Matz.

273
00:12:05.772 --> 00:12:07.473
But Bella is dead. so I don't think

274
00:12:07.507 --> 00:12:10.677
we need to worry about
her reputation right now.

275
00:12:10.710 --> 00:12:11.811
Who is Trey?

276
00:12:11.911 --> 00:12:13.630
Why did she want to destroy him?

277
00:12:16.140 --> 00:12:19.118
We're not trying to taint
anybody's legacy here.

278
00:12:19.185 --> 00:12:21.387
We're just trying to find
the person who shot her.

279
00:12:21.454 --> 00:12:24.215
[SIGHS] I understand.

280
00:12:24.282 --> 00:12:29.721
And if I'm being honest. I
think Trey could be involved.

281
00:12:29.787 --> 00:12:31.731
I never liked him.

282
00:12:31.831 --> 00:12:35.868
From day one. he was
a phony and so obvious.

283
00:12:35.902 --> 00:12:38.229
But Bella didn't see it.

284
00:12:38.329 --> 00:12:41.132
not until the last few weeks.

285
00:12:41.199 --> 00:12:43.176
Then it all came crashing down.

286
00:12:43.242 --> 00:12:45.678
Okay. this is good.

287
00:12:45.712 --> 00:12:48.381
Let's start at the beginning.

288
00:12:48.414 --> 00:12:50.149
Who the hell is Trey?

289
00:12:50.250 --> 00:12:52.085
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC]

290
00:12:52.151 --> 00:12:56.422
We talked to Bella's lawyer. Ellis Matz.

291
00:12:56.522 --> 00:12:59.359
He's not a big fan of yours. Trey.

292
00:12:59.425 --> 00:13:02.328
I'm not a big fan of his. so
I guess that makes us even.

293
00:13:02.362 --> 00:13:06.311
Well. not really. because
he's not spending Bella's money

294
00:13:06.312 --> 00:13:08.001
to buy lavish gifts for his mistresses.

295
00:13:08.067 --> 00:13:10.503
Ellis has no idea what
he's talking about.

296
00:13:10.603 --> 00:13:11.971
Really?

297
00:13:12.005 --> 00:13:15.141
So Bella just made it up
one day. out of the blue?

298
00:13:15.208 --> 00:13:20.046
She texts. "I cannot
believe Trey did this to me."

299
00:13:20.146 --> 00:13:22.515
It's possible. She was very emotional.

300
00:13:22.582 --> 00:13:24.450
Can you believe this prick?

301
00:13:24.550 --> 00:13:25.885
Why don't you help me out here. Trey?

302
00:13:25.985 --> 00:13:28.054
I just want to be clear.

303
00:13:28.154 --> 00:13:34.560
So you moved to the big
city from Worcester. Mass.

304
00:13:34.661 --> 00:13:37.797
lost your Boston accent.
started pronouncing your Rs.

305
00:13:37.864 --> 00:13:41.292
You changed your name
from Johnny O'Malley

306
00:13:41.392 --> 00:13:47.807
to Tate Harris III. Trey for short?

307
00:13:47.907 --> 00:13:48.907
Yeah.

308
00:13:48.975 --> 00:13:50.677
Not a crime to reinvent yourself. is it?

309
00:13:50.710 --> 00:13:54.614
No. but it is a crime to shoot your wife

310
00:13:54.714 --> 00:13:58.069
because she wants a divorce.
because she's figured out

311
00:13:58.075 --> 00:13:59.243
that you're spending all her money

312
00:13:59.310 --> 00:14:01.554
on hookers and cocaine.

313
00:14:01.654 --> 00:14:03.756
I was home sick watching TV

314
00:14:03.856 --> 00:14:05.992
the day Bella was killed.

315
00:14:15.326 --> 00:14:17.328
We looked at all the
video surveillance we have.

316
00:14:17.395 --> 00:14:19.072
and there's nothing
that disproves his alibi.

317
00:14:19.105 --> 00:14:21.065
So he was at home in Pound Ridge

318
00:14:21.132 --> 00:14:22.834
- at the time of the murder?
- I'm not saying that.

319
00:14:22.900 --> 00:14:24.268
I'm saying we got nothing
that says he wasn't.

320
00:14:24.335 --> 00:14:26.971
I just got access to his
credit card information.

321
00:14:27.004 --> 00:14:28.348
Anything good?

322
00:14:28.414 --> 00:14:31.250
Nothing obvious. No Uber rides or tolls.

323
00:14:31.284 --> 00:14:35.079
But he bought a burner phone
at Best Buy four days ago.

324
00:14:35.146 --> 00:14:38.149
Well. that sounds interesting to me.

325
00:14:40.593 --> 00:14:43.162
We know about the burner
phone you bought in the Bronx.

326
00:14:43.262 --> 00:14:44.597
So?

327
00:14:44.697 --> 00:14:47.133
So most law-abiding citizens

328
00:14:47.233 --> 00:14:48.768
up in Pound Ridge don't buy those.

329
00:14:48.835 --> 00:14:50.528
Yeah. they still prefer
old-fashioned iPhones

330
00:14:50.628 --> 00:14:51.971
'cause they're not
worried about being tracked

331
00:14:52.071 --> 00:14:54.532
- or leaving a digital footprint.
- Made us curious.

332
00:14:54.632 --> 00:14:57.376
So curious. we called every
car service in Pound Ridge.

333
00:14:57.443 --> 00:14:59.245
and Darien. and Greenwich.

334
00:14:59.312 --> 00:15:01.414
I'll be damned. but one of
them actually had a record

335
00:15:01.447 --> 00:15:03.850
of a client asking for a
7:00 a.m. pickup the morning

336
00:15:03.950 --> 00:15:05.318
that your wife was killed.

337
00:15:05.418 --> 00:15:08.020
And the destination was 25th and Park.

338
00:15:08.054 --> 00:15:09.714
five blocks from the crime scene.

339
00:15:09.781 --> 00:15:11.215
And he drove the client
home to Pound Ridge

340
00:15:11.282 --> 00:15:12.458
30 minutes after the murder.

341
00:15:12.558 --> 00:15:15.128
And this is where it
gets really interesting.

342
00:15:15.161 --> 00:15:18.222
The client asked for
the pickup and drop-off

343
00:15:18.322 --> 00:15:20.633
to be at the corner of Pleasant Drive

344
00:15:20.733 --> 00:15:24.128
and Woodlawn Road. which
is in a secluded section

345
00:15:24.195 --> 00:15:27.006
of Pound Ridge with no security cameras.

346
00:15:27.039 --> 00:15:29.734
And he paid cash.

347
00:15:29.834 --> 00:15:32.078
Time to start talking. Trey.

348
00:15:32.178 --> 00:15:34.113
I have no idea what
you're talking about.

349
00:15:34.180 --> 00:15:41.053
♪ ♪

350
00:15:41.087 --> 00:15:42.255
You good?

351
00:15:51.389 --> 00:15:54.600
You sure you don't want to
tell us your side of the story?

352
00:15:56.068 --> 00:15:58.204
Here's my side of the story.

353
00:15:58.237 --> 00:16:00.540
I had nothing to do with this.

354
00:16:00.573 --> 00:16:02.942
And that's all I have to say.

355
00:16:03.042 --> 00:16:04.610
Well. sit down. Sit your ass down.

356
00:16:04.677 --> 00:16:06.212
I'm done talking. so if you'd excuse me.

357
00:16:06.279 --> 00:16:08.673
No. we don't. Turn around.

358
00:16:08.739 --> 00:16:11.551
Tate Harris III. you are under arrest

359
00:16:11.584 --> 00:16:14.120
for the murder of Bella Ross.

360
00:16:21.461 --> 00:16:24.297
This was a cold-blooded
execution. Your Honor.

361
00:16:24.397 --> 00:16:26.265
The defendant's wife. Bella Ross.

362
00:16:26.299 --> 00:16:28.601
was not only planning to divorce him.

363
00:16:28.668 --> 00:16:31.504
but to claw back the money
he had stolen from her.

364
00:16:31.571 --> 00:16:33.940
In addition to his obvious motive.

365
00:16:34.006 --> 00:16:36.909
he repeatedly lied to
police about his whereabouts

366
00:16:37.009 --> 00:16:38.269
on the day of the murder.

367
00:16:38.302 --> 00:16:41.539
- We seek remand. Your Honor.
- Ms. Witt?

368
00:16:41.639 --> 00:16:44.484
The prosecution's
case is shockingly thin

369
00:16:44.550 --> 00:16:46.919
and lacking substance. like
one of those supermodels

370
00:16:46.953 --> 00:16:49.380
his wife used to hire
to strut down the runway.

371
00:16:49.447 --> 00:16:50.481
Watch it. Ms. Witt.

372
00:16:50.548 --> 00:16:52.091
I was just trying to make a point.

373
00:16:52.158 --> 00:16:53.492
No. you were just trying to be cute.

374
00:16:53.559 --> 00:16:55.219
and I don't do cute. So move on.

375
00:16:55.319 --> 00:16:56.762
I apologize.

376
00:16:56.796 --> 00:17:00.867
The defense is requesting
bail in the amount of $500.000.

377
00:17:00.933 --> 00:17:01.934
Denied.

378
00:17:02.001 --> 00:17:03.803
The defendant is hereby remanded.

379
00:17:03.870 --> 00:17:05.438
Your Honor. there is no murder weapon.

380
00:17:05.538 --> 00:17:07.565
- no fingerprints. no blood.
- [GAVEL SLAMS]

381
00:17:07.632 --> 00:17:08.708
Next case.

382
00:17:08.774 --> 00:17:11.802
[CAMERAS CLICKING]

383
00:17:15.248 --> 00:17:17.450
The defense attorney
described the State's case

384
00:17:17.483 --> 00:17:19.385
as shockingly thin and lacking...

385
00:17:19.452 --> 00:17:22.655
The press is really running
with this model metaphor.

386
00:17:22.688 --> 00:17:25.091
Shockingly thin and lacking substance?

387
00:17:25.157 --> 00:17:27.660
It's more quippy than true.

388
00:17:27.693 --> 00:17:29.854
And I'm. of course. offended on behalf

389
00:17:29.921 --> 00:17:31.464
of hardworking models everywhere.

390
00:17:31.497 --> 00:17:33.065
As you should be.

391
00:17:33.165 --> 00:17:35.134
Sadly. the attorney
isn't totally off-base.

392
00:17:35.201 --> 00:17:36.761
and the case is highly circumstantial.

393
00:17:36.861 --> 00:17:38.029
So it seems.

394
00:17:38.095 --> 00:17:39.505
Hard to prove murder
beyond a reasonable doubt

395
00:17:39.538 --> 00:17:41.307
without some physical evidence.

396
00:17:41.340 --> 00:17:43.834
Fortunately. our defendant
is just despicable enough...

397
00:17:43.868 --> 00:17:45.011
[PHONE BUZZES]

398
00:17:45.077 --> 00:17:47.780
I think we might just pull it off.

399
00:17:47.880 --> 00:17:51.017
- Ah.
- What is it?

400
00:17:51.050 --> 00:17:54.170
Brady just got an anonymous
tip about the murder weapon.

401
00:17:54.203 --> 00:17:56.055
Well. I take back what I said.

402
00:17:57.857 --> 00:18:00.126
I gotta tell you. man. I am 0 for 90

403
00:18:00.226 --> 00:18:02.428
- on anonymous tips.
- Don't go dark on me. Vince.

404
00:18:02.528 --> 00:18:04.355
Just stating the facts. man.

405
00:18:04.388 --> 00:18:07.166
- Got something.
- 9-millimeter?

406
00:18:07.233 --> 00:18:09.201
Yes. sir.

407
00:18:09.235 --> 00:18:11.504
- Your luck is changing. Vince.
- Maybe.

408
00:18:11.537 --> 00:18:12.872
What's that mean?

409
00:18:12.905 --> 00:18:14.273
It means when something's
too good to be true.

410
00:18:14.340 --> 00:18:16.842
- it usually is.
- Damn. I can't win with you.

411
00:18:16.943 --> 00:18:20.196
It's in the genes. man.

412
00:18:20.229 --> 00:18:23.749
All right. let's get that
to ballistics right away.

413
00:18:26.686 --> 00:18:29.146
Wait. What are you saying?

414
00:18:29.246 --> 00:18:31.724
That my gun was used to kill Bella Ross?

415
00:18:31.757 --> 00:18:33.960
- That is correct.
- [LAUGHS]

416
00:18:34.026 --> 00:18:35.227
That's impossible.

417
00:18:35.294 --> 00:18:36.495
Not according to the ballistics report

418
00:18:36.596 --> 00:18:38.965
- that we just got.
- Let's start at the beginning.

419
00:18:39.031 --> 00:18:40.533
- Do you own a gun?
- Yeah.

420
00:18:40.600 --> 00:18:42.735
- 9-millimeter Glock?
- Yes.

421
00:18:42.802 --> 00:18:44.604
I took it to a shooting
range in Brooklyn

422
00:18:44.670 --> 00:18:47.039
a few years ago and
shot off a few rounds.

423
00:18:47.139 --> 00:18:49.342
but that was it.

424
00:18:49.408 --> 00:18:50.601
I literally haven't touched it since.

425
00:18:50.668 --> 00:18:53.012
Where do you keep the gun? Here?

426
00:18:53.112 --> 00:18:56.115
Yeah. in my bedroom.

427
00:19:05.458 --> 00:19:07.126
Nice and slow. please.

428
00:19:08.961 --> 00:19:11.797
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC]

429
00:19:11.897 --> 00:19:16.135
♪ ♪

430
00:19:16.202 --> 00:19:18.104
This is where I kept it.

431
00:19:18.137 --> 00:19:19.463
Well. like I said. I haven't touched it

432
00:19:19.530 --> 00:19:21.307
or even thought about it in years.

433
00:19:23.776 --> 00:19:26.345
This is you and Tate Harris?

434
00:19:26.412 --> 00:19:27.947
Yeah?

435
00:19:27.980 --> 00:19:30.216
You guys were friends?

436
00:19:30.282 --> 00:19:31.417
Sort of.

437
00:19:31.450 --> 00:19:33.778
Has he ever been to your apartment?

438
00:19:33.811 --> 00:19:34.811
A few times.

439
00:19:34.854 --> 00:19:36.789
When was the last time?

440
00:19:36.856 --> 00:19:39.316
A few weeks ago. I had a dinner party.

441
00:19:39.383 --> 00:19:41.594
- Was he in your bedroom?
- [GROANS]

442
00:19:41.727 --> 00:19:45.164
- But he was here.
- Yeah. yeah. For sure.

443
00:19:45.264 --> 00:19:50.803
♪ ♪

444
00:19:50.836 --> 00:19:53.839
Hey. any luck tracking down
who made that anonymous tip?

445
00:19:53.906 --> 00:19:55.674
Yeah. call was made from a burner phone.

446
00:19:55.741 --> 00:19:57.610
Pinged off a tower on
the Upper West Side.

447
00:19:57.643 --> 00:19:59.879
Is that where Tate's lawyer lives?

448
00:19:59.979 --> 00:20:01.847
78th and Columbus.

449
00:20:01.947 --> 00:20:04.241
So Tate told her the
gun belonged to Dutch.

450
00:20:04.308 --> 00:20:05.518
She calls up the police.

451
00:20:05.618 --> 00:20:07.119
tells them where to
find it. thinking. what.

452
00:20:07.153 --> 00:20:09.155
it might help create reasonable doubt?

453
00:20:09.221 --> 00:20:13.592
Maybe. but we obviously can't prove it.

454
00:20:13.659 --> 00:20:14.794
The party guests?

455
00:20:14.927 --> 00:20:16.662
Yeah. they all confirmed Tate was there.

456
00:20:16.696 --> 00:20:18.431
but nobody saw him in Dutch's bedroom.

457
00:20:18.497 --> 00:20:20.066
Telling the truth?

458
00:20:20.166 --> 00:20:22.760
Nobody there was exactly
thrilled to be talking to me.

459
00:20:22.827 --> 00:20:24.236
Well. if nothing else.

460
00:20:24.303 --> 00:20:26.238
we can establish Dutch owned the gun.

461
00:20:26.305 --> 00:20:27.740
he kept it in his apartment.

462
00:20:27.840 --> 00:20:29.608
and Tate Harris was in that apartment

463
00:20:29.675 --> 00:20:31.168
four days prior to the murder.

464
00:20:31.202 --> 00:20:32.870
Yeah. it's not perfect.

465
00:20:32.937 --> 00:20:35.181
No. it's not. but
physically connects him

466
00:20:35.214 --> 00:20:36.415
to the murder weapon.

467
00:20:36.515 --> 00:20:38.209
Gives the jury one more piece of data

468
00:20:38.275 --> 00:20:40.636
to support our theory of the case.

469
00:20:44.123 --> 00:20:47.626
The defendant was married
to Bella Ross for six years.

470
00:20:47.726 --> 00:20:52.022
but their relationship was hardly equal.

471
00:20:52.056 --> 00:20:55.401
You see. Bella financed the defendant's

472
00:20:55.468 --> 00:20:59.738
fabulous lifestyle and his
failed business ventures.

473
00:20:59.805 --> 00:21:03.242
And then. about a week
prior to her death.

474
00:21:03.309 --> 00:21:06.011
she discovered that he
had been lying to her

475
00:21:06.045 --> 00:21:08.781
about pretty much everything.

476
00:21:08.848 --> 00:21:11.542
She realized he was a fraud.

477
00:21:11.575 --> 00:21:14.019
Nothing he said was real.

478
00:21:14.086 --> 00:21:19.150
even his name. Tate Harris III.

479
00:21:19.216 --> 00:21:22.027
His real name is John O'Malley.

480
00:21:22.094 --> 00:21:25.364
So Bella told her
lawyer and the defendant

481
00:21:25.498 --> 00:21:26.932
that she wanted a divorce.

482
00:21:26.999 --> 00:21:29.101
She was also planning
to sue the defendant

483
00:21:29.168 --> 00:21:31.904
to recover all the money
that he had borrowed

484
00:21:31.937 --> 00:21:34.665
or stolen from her during the six years

485
00:21:34.765 --> 00:21:36.208
that they were married.

486
00:21:36.242 --> 00:21:39.912
However. the defendant
wasn't ready to give up

487
00:21:39.979 --> 00:21:43.574
his extravagant
lifestyle. and in his mind.

488
00:21:43.607 --> 00:21:46.085
the only way to avoid
that was to make sure

489
00:21:46.118 --> 00:21:48.754
Bella Ross was dead before
she filed for divorce.

490
00:21:48.821 --> 00:21:52.291
So with an eye on inheriting
Bella's vast fortune.

491
00:21:52.358 --> 00:21:55.227
he stole a gun from
his friend's apartment

492
00:21:55.294 --> 00:21:58.798
and he assassinated her.

493
00:22:03.702 --> 00:22:06.372
By all accounts. Bella Ross led

494
00:22:06.472 --> 00:22:08.007
an extraordinary life.

495
00:22:08.107 --> 00:22:11.177
She was wealthy.
accomplished. respected.

496
00:22:11.277 --> 00:22:13.704
She owned luxurious homes in New York.

497
00:22:13.771 --> 00:22:15.014
Los Angeles. and London.

498
00:22:15.114 --> 00:22:18.042
She did what she wanted
with whom she wanted.

499
00:22:18.142 --> 00:22:21.453
And when a woman leads a life that

500
00:22:21.487 --> 00:22:24.548
is this extraordinary. this excessive.

501
00:22:24.615 --> 00:22:28.986
she tends to make a
lot of bitter enemies.

502
00:22:29.053 --> 00:22:33.132
Tate Harris did not kill Bella Ross.

503
00:22:33.165 --> 00:22:35.125
We will provide evidence
that proves this.

504
00:22:35.159 --> 00:22:38.037
that proves that he was
home in Pound Ridge. sick.

505
00:22:38.137 --> 00:22:41.131
watching a TV show when
Bella Ross was killed.

506
00:22:41.165 --> 00:22:43.809
So if Tate Harris didn't kill her.

507
00:22:43.842 --> 00:22:47.112
then who did? Honestly. I don't know.

508
00:22:47.146 --> 00:22:50.808
My job is to present
evidence that forces you

509
00:22:50.841 --> 00:22:55.354
to reconsider the prosecution's
flawed theory of the crime.

510
00:22:55.454 --> 00:22:58.657
and to determine whether or
not the prosecution proved

511
00:22:58.724 --> 00:23:02.294
beyond a reasonable doubt that
Tate Harris killed Bella Ross.

512
00:23:02.361 --> 00:23:05.731
When this trial is over.

513
00:23:05.798 --> 00:23:08.267
I am highly confident that
the answer to that question

514
00:23:08.334 --> 00:23:10.536
is a resounding no.

515
00:23:10.603 --> 00:23:13.539
[TENSE MUSIC]

516
00:23:13.639 --> 00:23:18.043
♪ ♪

517
00:23:24.450 --> 00:23:26.710
Sounds like the defense
is gonna try like hell

518
00:23:26.777 --> 00:23:29.722
to exploit Bella Ross's
decadent lifestyle.

519
00:23:29.822 --> 00:23:31.323
